History of the brand:
The IBM innovator enters the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find the word that best expresses the IMB strategy, the closest one is likely to be “long-lasting.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The company's longevity was established by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson, senior.
He believed in his motto, according to which many world problems can be easily solved if people want to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant revolved (and also the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
What’s more, it was the foundation of the corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means a constant movement towards the future.
IBM survived and thrived for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, even though it was not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first hundred years, this has allowed us to transform technology, business and company.
