Dynamics of prices for travel since 1989
Until 1989, only five state tourism agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
As travel to the West was severely restricted, tourism agencies at the time mostly sold tours to socialist bloc countries.
Thus, on holiday Czech tourists traveled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia. Then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, which led to significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual trips to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel by himself, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation from that country was necessary; otherwise individual travel was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered to travel to the West, but it was either necessary to stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or to have "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Currency clearance was necessary for travel to the West. It was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without currency permission it was impossible to obtain money (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most often the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the appearance of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit remains to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989, holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are no longer aware of is that until 1989 we could not freely visit the most popular present-day Croatia, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa to neighboring countries of Western Europe was abolished, which marked the beginning of a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not be satisfied with their travels to the West. Everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, as their income at the time was not enough for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism during that period was the desire to bring their own food (canned food, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of the freely convertible Czech krone. After decades, our tourists can finally freely buy the Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income increased, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, the increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights performed by charter airlines. Compared to the past, airline flights have now become incredibly cheap thanks to the ability to order wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s the Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all the developed countries of the world except the United States. This made our travels even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution occurred in 2000. The great demand led to the historically first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have brought Czech tourists to warm exotic countries. This winter flights from the Czech Republic will be sent in twelve exotic directions.
Currently, about 100 thousand Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States cancelled the need to obtain a visa for Czech tourists. Our country thus has forever joined the most developed countries in the world.
For the first time in history in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15 thousand kroner per person during a holiday abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
