It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This slightly edited material became the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which airs at Landmark Theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of a detailed interview, Jobs seems unusually willing to explain his technological philosophy and business strategy here.
And unbelievably thoughtful.
At four different moments during the interview, there are large intervals between questions and answers - reflections of 10-15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to say more accurately.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems irritated by Kringley’s questions, making him move faster to issues or phenomena of greater importance.
