About large companies that lose energy:
Long before he headed Apple’s revival, Jobs accurately predicted how many industry leaders would go wrong in seeing the situation and lose control of their market share.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make the best copy or printer, and what?”
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company does not become more successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [these are the types of people] who eventually come to the management of companies, and people who make a product are pushed out of the decision-making platform.
The genius of the product that led to this monopolistic position is pushed out by people who have no idea of the difference between good and bad products - the required skill.
This is what happened to Xerox.
Xerox could take over the entire information technology industry.
It could be ten times bigger, it could be a 90's Microsoft...
They were defeated by victory.
Innovation as a Form of Art:
“A great idea of a great product separates a huge amount of skilled labor... when you twist a great idea, it changes and grows.”
You will learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises that you need to go to – some things you won’t be able to force to make electrons, glass, robots or factories.
You need to keep in mind 5,000 ideas – these concepts – by connecting them all together...
In the end, it all comes down to taste – it all comes down to trying to express yourself in the best that people have ever produced, and later – trying to bring it into what you’re doing.
Picasso said that good artists are copying, great artists are stealing.
It has always been a shame to steal great ideas.
Part of what made McIntosh famous was that the people who worked on him were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happened to become the best experts in the field of information technology in the world.
