Who influenced you as a bass player?
There are so many.
Among the first to come to mind, Gizer Butler, John Antwill, C.J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski ...
There are so many of them that I can talk all day about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam achieve success in maintaining the topicality of the range, despite the fact that it is no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about him, he reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone who appeared at the same time, and if it matters now, I think it's great because it's music that's worth listening to, and the teams are like Mudhoney.
At first, your music was darker, and now it has become more positive.
How would you explain this change?
It’s interesting because, I think, there are a few songs on the album that may seem easier, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very dark, although they may sound a bit positive.
From both of them, when Ed was playing them, I was crying, when I was listening to them, these songs are very dark.
I think that when you grow up and in your life there was some trauma and you lost a family member or friend, these events begin to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that for me.
So, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to create dark music.
