MSS announces fat cell gene search program
Social Protection Leads Research to Find the Obesity Gene in Children and Young People; It’s Supported by IPN Specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, which has been named the protocol "Child and adolescent obesity genetics", which will provide an estimate of the signs associated with obesity.
In a statement, the head of the Division of Medical Research in Biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz Lopez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietitians and social workers had been assembled.
This team is supported by specialists and graduates of the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (prescribed or not) is invited to take part by going to MSSI sports centers, taking part in the study, to the Valley of Mexico, where every Saturday, from 8:00 a.m., tests will be conducted with the participation of children.
He stressed that the protocol began to run at the sports center in Cuautemoca (in the west of the state of Mexico), and since October 8, the events have been held at the sports center in Nesaualcoyotla (east of the state of Mexico).
After the goal of attracting between 500 and 600 children is achieved, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (South Mexico) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (North Mexico).
He explained that the aim of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
November 14 will be World Diabetes Day, and the main goal is to gather three thousand children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 with parental permission and under their supervision to fill out individual nutrition questionnaires.
They are also asked about physical activity and the history of family hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to the appearance of diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), blood pressure and glucose levels, fats, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic analysis will be carried out (to identify genes that are associated with childhood oedema).
Cruz Lopez said the study reflects the concerns of health care professionals about worrying about weight gain among children.
In medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006, it is said that there was a growth in just 6 years: in the case of boys, 77 percent suffered from obesity, in the case of girls, 47 percent; in the case of excess weight, there was also a significant growth," said MSSI.
He said the rationale for searching for markers was based on the fact that the country’s population differs from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans are 65 percent descendants of American Indians, 30 percent descendants of Europeans, and five percent descendants of Africans, and this condition has affected genes that are linked to diabetes and overweight.
He explained that basically, the consequence of obesity genetics is the body’s inability to burn off the excess energy we consume (calories) and it is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that a direct benefit for participants is a comprehensive assessment of children who can identify whether they have any degree of excess weight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acants) and forearms means the likelihood of a violation of metabolism and even prediabetes.
With the information being treated with complete confidentiality, the doctor transmits it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the dimensions and changes in the lifestyle that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main reasons that provoke excess weight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or a lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV, and using transportation to keep small spaces.
This is also due to high calorie intake, i.e. an increase in consumption of sweet beverages and carbohydrates (tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
