Democracy is a valuable acquisition, but at the same time it is fragile.
The European continent must remember that by inventing it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, in the 20th century it survived the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, and colonels in Greece.
Some believed that in order for democracy to be finally enthralled by its enemies, it was enough to organize the vote and make it as direct as possible.
Since the time of Napoleon the “Little” it is known that this comes from the superficiality of thought.
A universal vote, although a mandatory condition for democracy, is not a sufficient condition for it and may even become a “tool of repression,” as philosopher-Republican Etienne Vashro once said.
No, democracy requires much more - public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of authorities, education, education, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The European crisis we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but first and foremost it is a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this respect, the palindrome of a true-liest Greek referendum will have a double illuminating effect, demonstrating both the need for a serious change in policy and the unpleasant feeling of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality must be understood in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front line of the struggle for democracy has now shifted and, in the opinion of many, the Republican soldiers are now aiming not in that direction.
We will not win anything by demanding a series of national referendums, organized as necessary and in a chaotic manner.
Card Blanch for an absolute European monarch or a jump with his legs tied to the abyss of nationalism – what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not dream of a guillotine, but of a joint, clear and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the pan-European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and it is not known how many more will have to be listed, because there is only one crisis - the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is subject to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffers from its weakness and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
Many are concerned about the transfer of Europe's sovereignty, but the whole of Europe is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
It is necessary to urgently restore the management of the European project under the sovereignty of the people.
Because only by working together, Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of everyone’s debt, free themselves from the markets and prepare for the future by investing in it.
Exiting the crisis will require decisions at the pan-European level, and they cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, without leading us to disaster.
After a long discussion of this proposal, the Socialists and Jacques Delors all now demand a European economic government.
Let's go.
But to imagine it without a stronger economic, political and democratic integration that has come into being is another madness and a new obstacle.
We need to start a new phase of European construction.
In order to establish a republic in France, it was necessary to “create” republicans.
Revolutions of interest would not be enough.
This lesson remains in force.
We must build a Europe that is united at the economic level.
This can only be done by creating a more democratic Europe at the political level, of the real people’s European sovereignty.
In order to create Europe, let us create Europeans.
