The North Stream, a new gateway for Russian gas entry into Europe.
The North Stream gas pipeline, which connects Western Europe and Russia directly to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, is launched.
It is estimated to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between the performance of the orchestra and exquisite snacks, in the opening of the North Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany under water.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fijon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rutte have returned a symbolic valve that controls Russian gas's entry into the Western European network.
According to the new gas pipeline, 27.5 million additional cubic meters of gas will enter Western Europe each year on the first pipeline of 1,224 km, connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline is expected to be ready by the end of 2012, providing a total supply of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas equivalent to all of France’s consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met with fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream will actually allow you to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding passing through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose part of their power: it will be harder for them to influence Russia, threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debates, Warsaw did not stop before comparing the North Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin in order to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of its supplies.
But at the cost of Europe’s depletion of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to achieve its understanding of the direct union between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already at an end.
“This pipeline is part of cooperation with Russia, it’s a new artery that organically connects us,” said Francois Fijon, opening the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
Underwater pipeline is made of steel, enclosed in concrete, to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the minefields left from the Second World War.
“One hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller, North Stream’s press secretary.
It was also necessary to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
Pipeline is a long metal snake with a weight equal to 242 Eiffel Towers, without gaps along its entire length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but project managers gave up on it because Sweden was not thrilled that the Russian state-owned company would forever settle on its shores.
“In the event of an accident, we will shut down the gas flow in less than a minute,” Jens Mueller said.
So, in the case of a leak of gas contained in the gas pipeline, it will go into the air.
But this seems unlikely to the designers, who designed seams designed for the flow only once every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline will be carried out by a submarine robot that pulls the ship, for external observation, as well as by the apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
The cigar-shaped device is inserted into the pipe 1 meter in diameter and is pushed forward by a flow of gas.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it provides accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for 50 years without the need for any minor repairs.
Gas circulation is carried out only at the expense of its pressure.
It is 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called the North Stream, which was tasked with building and operating a gas pipeline.
Its headquarters are located in Z<0xC3><0xBC>ge, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Gazprom then leased the company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gazprom will pay for the full amount, regardless of how much gas will actually be transported,” says Jens Mueller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work will be <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 thousand million for two pipelines.
GDF Suez’s investment will be about 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will pay their costs, because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The gas pipeline exits the Baltic Sea in Lubmina on a sandy shore, planted with coniferous trees.
Valves with a height of 4.5 meters form an outlet gas terminal.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before it can be transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity it will be 3 million per hour, and in 2012 it will be 6 million.
