About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week of disability employment begins today.
Despite the public welfare policy that began in 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled is still two times higher than the average, namely 19% versus 9% for the general population.
Disturbing?
“No,” said Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of employment for people with disabilities.
“In 15 years, we have made significant progress.”
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not 2, but 3 times higher.”
“There is still a lot of work ahead.”
It should be said that there are still many obstacles to employment for the disabled.
Among them, more elderly: 37% older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a rather low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree, and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for people with disabilities versus 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to get back to work and that are the essence of the problem,” said Christian Graben, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire people with disabilities.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association on Cité’s order showed that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and “represented themselves as total people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally undervalued.”
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6% of the disabled employees set out in the law passed in 1987.
